04445nam a22005535i 9780228002536DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280025367 a10.1515/97802280025362doi  a(DE-B1597)655085  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHG654b.G48 2020eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a332.4/971090342231 aGettler, Brian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aColonialism's Currency :bMoney State and First Nations in Canada 1820-1950 /cBrian Gettler. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource :b3 maps, 6 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on the History of Quebec/Études d'histoire du Québec ;v3900tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tMoney and Meaning under Settler Colonialism -- tMoney: A Technology of Settler Colonialism -- tImagining Money as a Threat in the 1820s and 1830s -- tThe Formation of the Territorial State -- tFur-Trade Money and the Coming of the State in Saguenay-Lac-Saint-Jean -- tTreaty Money: A Symbol of Sovereignty in Western James Bay -- tReserving Currency in Indigenous-State Relations -- tLand, Natural Resources, and Fiscal Control in Mid-Nineteenth-Century Quebec -- tRelief, Rights, and Resources: State Control of Money in the Twentieth Century -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMoney, often portrayed as a straightforward representation of market value, is also a political force, a technology for remaking space and population. This was especially true in nineteenth- and twentieth-century Canada, where money - in many forms - provided an effective means of disseminating colonial social values, laying claim to national space, and disciplining colonized peoples. Colonialism's Currency analyzes the historical experiences and interactions of three distinct First Nations - the Wendat of Wendake, the Innu of Mashteuiatsh, and the Moose Factory Cree - with monetary forms and practices created by colonial powers. Whether treaty payments and welfare provisions such as the paper vouchers favoured by the Department of Indian Affairs, the Canadian Dominion's standardized paper notes, or the "made beaver" (the Hudson's Bay Company's money of account), each monetary form allowed the state to communicate and enforce political, economic, and cultural sovereignty over Indigenous peoples and their lands. Surveying a range of historical cases, Brian Gettler shows how currency simultaneously placed First Nations beyond the bounds of settler society while justifying colonial interventions in their communities. Testifying to the destructive and the legitimizing power of money, Colonialism's Currency is an intriguing exploration of the complex relationship between First Nations and the state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aImperialism. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxGovernment relations. 0aMoneyxPolitical aspectszCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aMoneyxPolitical aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMoneyxSocial aspectszCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aMoneyxSocial aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMoneyzCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aMoneyzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800253640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228002536423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228002536/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles